{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17613886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17613886"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:38:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:38:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16328"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16328"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9019"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116171"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9019","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9019"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16328"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98167"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7507"},{"type":"tags","id":"7517"},{"type":"tags","id":"8403"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21457"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21462"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116171"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe eye contains several protective layers of connective tissue that help maintain its structure and function.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical characteristics of the episclera?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dense irregular connective tissue, superficial to Tenon\u0027s capsule","Dense irregular connective tissue, deep to Tenon\u0027s capsule","Loose connective tissue, merges with scleral stroma","Loose connective tissue, superficial to Tenon\u0027s capsule","Dense regular connective tissue, merges with scleral stroma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe episclera is a layer of \u003Cstrong\u003Edense irregular connective tissue that lies deep to Tenon\u0027s capsule\u003C/strong\u003E. It is firmly attached to the underlying sclera and contains blood vessels that provide nutrition to the avascular sclera.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows: \u003Cstrong\u003EDense irregular connective tissue, superficial to Tenon\u0027s capsule\u003C/strong\u003E places the episclera in the wrong anatomical position, as it lies deep to, not superficial to, Tenon\u0027s capsule. \u003Cstrong\u003ELoose connective tissue, merges with scleral stroma\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eloose connective tissue, superficial to Tenon\u0027s capsule\u003C/strong\u003E both incorrectly describe the episclera as loose connective tissue when it is actually composed of dense connective tissue. \u003Cstrong\u003EDense regular connective tissue, merges with scleral stroma\u003C/strong\u003E correctly identifies the tissue as dense but incorrectly describes it as regular rather than irregular in arrangement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe episclera merges with the cornea at the limbus and plays an important role in the structural integrity and blood supply of the outer eye.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The episclera is a layer of dense irregular connective tissue located deep to Tenon\u0027s capsule and superficial to the sclera.","The episclera merges with the cornea at the limbus and contains blood vessels that nourish the sclera."],"references":["Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-Kels JM. Human ocular anatomy. Clin Dermatol. 2015 Mar-Apr;33(2):140-6. doi: 10.1016/j.clindermatol.2014.10.006. PMID: 25704934"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98167"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16328"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98167"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-27T19:16:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-27T19:18:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9019"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116171"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4